Core Assessment
Completeness
8/10
You've captured all the main entities — Books, Members, Authors, Borrowing, and a separate Member Information table. That covers the core of the problem nicely. One gap though: your Books table is missing basic book attributes like title, ISBN, genre, or publication year — without these, you can't actually identify which book is which. Adding a `title` column (at minimum) is essential.
At EASY level, capturing all key entities is the main win, and you've done that. Just round out the Books table with descriptive fields.
Relationship Accuracy
7/10
Your FK from Books → Authors is correct, and Borrowing → Books and Borrowing → Members are well-placed. However, there's a subtle issue: in the Borrowing table, you've marked `book_id` and `member_id` as UNIQUE. That means each book can only ever be borrowed once and each member can only borrow once across all time — which breaks the whole purpose of a borrowing history. Remove the UNIQUE constraint from those FK columns. Also, Books.author_id is UNIQUE, which would mean each author can only write one book — same issue.
Even at EASY, getting cardinality right matters. The UNIQUE-on-FK mistake is the biggest thing to fix here.
Normalization
6/10
You correctly split Authors into its own table — good instinct. But then you duplicated `author_first_name` and `author_last_name` back into Books, which defeats the purpose. If an author changes their name, you'd have to update it in two places. Just keep author_id in Books and look up the name via JOIN. Also, splitting Members into 'Members' and 'Member Information' feels unnecessary for a small library — and `member_phone_number` appears in both tables, which is classic duplication. Merge them into one Members table.
Normalization is a key learning goal at EASY. The author name duplication and the Members/Member Information split are the two things to clean up.
Normalization Notes:
The Main Normal Forms
1.	First Normal Form (1NF): Requires all column values to be atomic (indivisible). It bans multi-valued lists or repeating groups in a single cell. [1, 2, 3]
2.	Second Normal Form (2NF): Meets 1NF rules and ensures all non-key columns depend entirely on the primary key. It eliminates partial dependencies on composite keys. [1, 2]
3.	Third Normal Form (3NF): Meets 2NF rules and eliminates transitive dependencies. A non-key column cannot depend on another non-key column; it must depend only on the primary key. [1, 2, 3, 4]
Denormlization Notes:
Denormalization is the strategic process of adding controlled redundancy back into a database schema. It is almost always performed starting from a normalized baseline. [1, 2, 3]
•	Primary Goal: Maximize query execution speed and simplify data reads.
•	Core Mechanism: Merging tables or duplicating attributes across fields to dramatically reduce the need for computationally heavy JOIN operations. [1, 2, 3]

Integrity Constraints
7/10
Every table has a primary key — great. NOT NULL is used reasonably across required fields. Two things to tighten: (1) The UNIQUE constraints on FK columns in Borrowing and Books are incorrect as mentioned — they should not be unique. (2) `return_date` in Borrowing is NOT NULL, but a book that's currently checked out hasn't been returned yet — this column should be nullable so you can use `WHERE return_date IS NULL` to find currently borrowed books.
PK usage is solid. The nullable return_date is a small but important fix for the business logic.
