Advanced Concepts
•	Many-to-many relationships with junction tables (you'll need this when a book has multiple authors)
•	Junction Tables solve the many to many relationship. IE. many authors can write one book and one author can write many books. Throw them into a middle table with each of their primary keys as foreign keys to keep referential integrity. You can also add a composite primary key (student_id, course_id) or create a new primary key. This allows you to add more data.
•	Derived vs. stored data: when to compute something with a query vs. store it as a column
•	There is a fundamental trade-off between storage and compute. You need to actively consider storage costs, compute bottlenecks and query latency.
•	An intermediate engineer just writes a view. An experienced engineer explains the architectural trade-offs of how and where that derived data is served. Tell the interviewer you evaluate three approaches:
•	Approach A: Compute on the Fly (Virtual Views / CTEs)
•	You keep the data strictly stored as raw files and calculate the derived fields at the exact moment the user runs a query (using SQL Views or runtime transformations).
•	Pros: Zero extra storage cost; 100% accurate up to the second (no data staleness).
•	Cons: High compute cost. If 10,000 users query the dashboard daily, you pay to calculate that math 10,000 times.
•	Approach B: Materialization / Physical Storage (Pre-computation)
•	You calculate the derived data once (e.g., via a dbt pipeline or a Materialized View) and physically write the result back to the database.
•	Pros: Sub-second query performance. The heavy lifting is already done.
•	Cons: Storage overhead and data drift/staleness. If a raw transaction changes, your derived table is incorrect until the next sync pipeline runs.
•	The "Interview Mic-Drop": Framework for Decision Making
•	When the interviewer asks, "How do you decide whether to store it or derive it?" give them this checklist:
•	Query SLA vs. Batch Window: If an executive dashboard needs to load in under 2 seconds, I materialize (store) the derived aggregations. If it's an ad-hoc query run once a month, I compute it on the fly (derive).
•	Volatility of Logic: If the business logic for the derivation changes frequently (e.g., how the company defines "Active User"), I keep it derived via code/views so I only have to update the logic in one place. If I store it, I’d have to backfill petabytes of historical data.
•	Cost Economics: In modern cloud warehouses (Snowflake, BigQuery), storage is incredibly cheap, but compute can be expensive. I lean heavily toward pre-computing and storing highly complex, multi-stage joins to optimize cluster compute costs.

Code Examples
Quick Fixes
•	CREATE TABLE books ( book_id UUID PRIMARY KEY, title VARCHAR(500) NOT NULL, isbn VARCHAR(20) UNIQUE, author_id UUID NOT NULL REFERENCES authors(author_id), total_copies INTEGER NOT NULL, available_copies INTEGER NOT NULL );
•	CREATE TABLE borrowing ( borrowing_id UUID PRIMARY KEY, book_id UUID NOT NULL REFERENCES books(book_id), member_id UUID NOT NULL REFERENCES members(member_id), borrowed_date TIMESTAMP NOT NULL, due_date TIMESTAMP NOT NULL, return_date TIMESTAMP -- nullable: NULL means still borrowed );
Alternative Approaches
•	For multi-author books, create a junction table book_authors(book_id, author_id) instead of a single author_id FK on books — this is the next step up in modeling.
•	Instead of storing `low_stock` as a boolean, derive it from available_copies < threshold in a query. This way you never have stale flags to maintain.
 
