Your Borrowing → Books and Borrowing → Members FKs are correctly placed on the 'many' side — great work. However, there's a bug in your junction table: the FK on `books_and_authors_junction_table.id` references `Authors.author_id`, but `id` is the junction's own primary key — that's incorrect. The FK should be on the `author_id` column instead. Right now your model is essentially linking the junction's PK to authors, which breaks the many-to-many setup.
FK placement is the core skill at this level, and this one wiring mistake is the main thing holding the score back.
Normalization
7/10
The separation of Books, Authors, and the junction table is well done — that's textbook normalization for a many-to-many. A few things to clean up though: `low_stock` in Books is derivable from `number_of_copies_available` and shouldn't be stored. Similarly, `current_books_borrowed`, `total_borrowed_books`, and `total_borrowed_count` are aggregates that can be computed from the Borrowing table — storing them risks drift (e.g., a member returns a book and you forget to decrement the counter). Also, `currently_borrowed` in Borrowing is redundant since you can derive it from `return_date IS NULL`.
At EASY level, avoiding derived columns is a good habit to build early — it'll save you headaches in bigger schemas.
Integrity Constraints
8/10
Every table has a primary key, and you've marked PKs as NOT NULL UNIQUE — solid. ISBN is correctly UNIQUE, which is great since it's a natural identifier. A couple of gaps: Members has no UNIQUE constraint on phone or any natural key (consider adding an email column and marking it UNIQUE), and the junction table should have a composite UNIQUE on (book_id, author_id) to prevent duplicate author-book pairings.
Good baseline use of constraints — adding a UNIQUE on the member's natural identifier would round this out.
