Quick Fixes
•	CREATE TABLE books_authors ( book_id UUID NOT NULL REFERENCES books(book_id), author_id UUID NOT NULL REFERENCES authors(author_id), PRIMARY KEY (book_id, author_id) );
•	CREATE TABLE borrowing ( borrowing_transaction_id UUID PRIMARY KEY, book_id UUID NOT NULL REFERENCES books(book_id), member_id UUID NOT NULL REFERENCES members(member_id), borrowed_date TIMESTAMP NOT NULL, due_date TIMESTAMP NOT NULL, return_date TIMESTAMP -- NULL means currently borrowed );
Alternative Approaches
•	Instead of tracking `number_of_copies_available` as a counter, you could model each physical copy as its own row in a `book_copies` table — then availability is just `WHERE copy_id NOT IN (SELECT copy_id FROM borrowing WHERE return_date IS NULL)`. This scales better and tracks individual copy condition.
•	If you ever expand to multiple branches, add a `branches` table and put a `branch_id` FK on `book_copies` — your current schema would need restructuring for that, but the single-location constraint makes your current design fine for now.

